---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Claude Code Memory & Context Management"
  description="From the CLAUDE.md project handbook and auto memory notes, to /compact, /clear, and /context for keeping conversations lean — how to make Claude Code remember the right things in the right places."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container cc-memory">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Help Claude Code Get to Know You Better</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          Many people who start using Claude Code have the same feeling: "I told it this
          yesterday — why do I have to say it again today?" This isn't Claude Code being
          forgetful. Every new conversation simply starts from a fresh context window.
          This page will help you put the rules you want remembered in the right places.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Section 1: Two kinds of long-term memory -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Two Kinds of Long-Term Memory</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Claude Code isn't entirely without long-term memory. It mainly uses two mechanisms to
        carry important information into the next work session. They play different roles, so
        understanding the difference helps you decide what to put where.
      </p>

      <div class="compare-grid">
        <div class="compare-card compare-card--accent">
          <p class="compare-label">What you write for it</p>
          <p class="compare-title">CLAUDE.md</p>
          <p class="compare-desc">
            A "project handbook" that lives inside your project. Every time a new work session
            starts, Claude Code reads this file first. This is the right place for rules that
            describe how this project is normally done.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-card">
          <p class="compare-label">What it builds for itself</p>
          <p class="compare-title">auto memory</p>
          <p class="compare-desc">
            Work notes that Claude Code quietly builds up as it works. It remembers the things
            you often remind it about, the patterns that keep showing up, and lessons from
            debugging — so the next session starts with less friction.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In short: <strong>CLAUDE.md is the long-term rules you lay down; auto memory is the
        preferences and patterns Claude Code gradually picks up while working with you.</strong>
      </p>

      <!-- Section 2: CLAUDE.md -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">CLAUDE.md — The Project's Onboarding Handbook</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Think of CLAUDE.md as an onboarding handbook for Claude Code. The official guidance is
        to use it for <strong>build and test commands, code style, workflow rules, architecture
        decisions, and naming conventions</strong> — the kind of content that applies every
        time. Project-level CLAUDE.md files can live at <code>./CLAUDE.md</code> or
        <code>./.claude/CLAUDE.md</code>.
      </p>

      <div class="tip-card">
        <p class="tip-title">The fastest way to start</p>
        <p class="tip-body">
          Inside VS Code you don't have to start from scratch. Just type <code>/init</code> in
          the Claude Code chat box. Claude Code will scan your project and produce a starter
          CLAUDE.md, usually including the build commands, test setup, and conventions it can
          detect. If a CLAUDE.md already exists, <code>/init</code> won't overwrite it — it
          suggests additions instead.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        You can read it this way: CLAUDE.md stores the rules for "how this project is normally
        done". For example:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block"><code># Project Overview
An internal frontend project for the company quoting system.

# Commands
- Development: npm run dev
- Tests: npm test

# Development Rules
- Always use function components
- Prefer Tailwind for styling
- Run npm test before shipping any API change</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This kind of content fits CLAUDE.md well, because it isn't a one-off task — it's
        something that applies every time you work on this project.
      </p>

      <!-- Section 3: Keep it short -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Don't Write an Essay — Shorter Is More Useful</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Many beginners think, "If Claude Code is going to read this, I may as well stuff
        everything in." But it's actually the opposite — CLAUDE.md isn't "the longer the
        better". It should be <strong>short, clear, and easy to scan</strong>. The official
        guidance suggests keeping each CLAUDE.md under 200 lines and using markdown headings
        and bullet points to group rules. Because CLAUDE.md is loaded at the start of every
        session, a long one both eats context and drowns out the rules that matter.
      </p>

      <div class="info-card">
        <p class="info-title">A simple way to decide</p>
        <p class="info-body">
          If removing this line wouldn't make Claude Code any more likely to get things wrong,
          don't write it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="scenario-grid">
        <div class="scenario-card scenario-card--skip">
          <p class="scenario-tag scenario-tag--skip">— Not specific enough</p>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>Please write clean code</li>
            <li>Please keep the project structure consistent</li>
            <li>Remember to test after changes</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="scenario-note">Too abstract — Claude Code can't tell what "right" looks like.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="scenario-card scenario-card--good">
          <p class="scenario-tag scenario-tag--good">✓ Much better</p>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>Use 2-space indentation</li>
            <li>Put API handlers under <code>src/api/handlers/</code></li>
            <li>Run <code>npm test</code> before committing</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="scenario-note">Concrete and verifiable — easy for Claude Code to follow.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 4: auto memory -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">auto memory — Claude Code's Own Work Notes</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        On top of the CLAUDE.md you write by hand, Claude Code has another memory system called
        <strong>auto memory</strong>. It quietly records the things you remind it about, the
        patterns that recur in your project, and debugging lessons — so the next session starts
        on firmer ground.
      </p>

      <div class="path-card">
        <p class="path-label">Where does it live?</p>
        <p class="path-body">
          auto memory is <strong>not</strong> a <code>MEMORY.md</code> file you create in the
          project root. Instead, Claude Code writes it automatically to:
        </p>
        <pre class="path-code"><code>~/.claude/projects/&lt;project&gt;/memory/</code></pre>
        <p class="path-body">
          You may see topic files in there such as <code>debugging.md</code> or
          <code>api-conventions.md</code>. The <strong>first 200 lines or 25KB</strong> of
          <code>MEMORY.md</code> are loaded at the start of every new conversation; Claude Code
          reads the more detailed notes only when it needs them.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So you can split the work like this:
      </p>

      <div class="split-grid">
        <div class="split-card">
          <p class="split-head">CLAUDE.md is good for</p>
          <ul class="split-list">
            <li>This project uses pnpm</li>
            <li>Add tests before changing an API</li>
            <li>Components use PascalCase</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="split-card split-card--soft">
          <p class="split-head">auto memory gradually remembers</p>
          <ul class="split-list">
            <li>The login-timeout case is what breaks most often here</li>
            <li>You care a lot about not renaming files casually</li>
            <li>Which fix worked for that specific error last time</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        To edit CLAUDE.md, manage auto memory, or inspect stored memory entries, type:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>/memory</code></pre>

      <div class="warning-card">
        <p class="warning-title">⚠ Heads up</p>
        <p class="warning-body">
          auto memory is <strong>local to your machine</strong> — it does not automatically
          sync with your team. Any rule the whole team should follow still belongs in the
          project's CLAUDE.md. Don't expect auto memory to carry it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 5: Cleaning up -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">When the Conversation Gets Long, Help Claude Code Clear Its Head</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Claude Code does remember the files you read, command output, chat history, CLAUDE.md,
        and auto memory for this session — but all of that shares the same context window. The
        longer you chat and the more files it has seen, the easier it is for its attention to
        drift toward older, less important content. When you notice a conversation has been
        running for a while and has seen a lot of files, it's a good moment to tidy up.
      </p>

      <div class="cmd-list">
        <article class="cmd-card">
          <div class="cmd-head">
            <span class="cmd-num">1</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="cmd-title">/compact</h3>
              <p class="cmd-alias">Compress a long chat down to the essentials</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="cmd-desc">
            Use this when you still want to continue the same task, but the context is getting
            cluttered. You can also tell Claude Code what to preserve during the compression.
          </p>
          <div class="cmd-example">
            <p class="cmd-example-label">Example</p>
            <code>/compact keep only the login flow, the API spec, and the bug I'm still fixing</code>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="cmd-card">
          <div class="cmd-head">
            <span class="cmd-num">2</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="cmd-title">/clear</h3>
              <p class="cmd-alias">Wipe this chat and start fresh</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="cmd-desc">
            Use this when your next task is completely unrelated. If you've just been fixing
            the login flow and now want Claude Code to redesign the homepage, don't stack it
            onto the same thread — clearing or starting a new conversation is much cleaner.
          </p>
          <div class="cmd-example">
            <p class="cmd-example-label">Example</p>
            <code>/clear</code>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="cmd-card">
          <div class="cmd-head">
            <span class="cmd-num">3</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="cmd-title">/context</h3>
              <p class="cmd-alias">Check what is actually using up space</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="cmd-desc">
            If the conversation feels sluggish or Claude Code starts missing the point but you
            aren't sure whether it's because the context is full, run <code>/context</code>
            first and see what is taking up the room.
          </p>
          <div class="cmd-example">
            <p class="cmd-example-label">Example</p>
            <code>/context</code>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="summary-card">
        <p class="summary-title">Key takeaways</p>
        <ul class="summary-list">
          <li><strong>CLAUDE.md</strong> — rules that apply every time. Keep them short, specific, and under 200 lines.</li>
          <li><strong>auto memory</strong> — Claude Code's own work notes. Local to your machine, not shared with the team.</li>
          <li><strong>/compact, /clear, /context</strong> — reach for these when the conversation starts feeling heavy.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .cc-memory {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Give paragraphs a bit more breathing room when they follow a card */
  .tip-card + .detail-paragraph,
  .path-card + .detail-paragraph,
  .split-grid + .detail-paragraph {
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
  }

  /* Compare cards (CLAUDE.md vs auto memory) */
  .compare-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .compare-card {
    padding: var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
  }

  .compare-card--accent {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .compare-label {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 600;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .compare-card--accent .compare-label {
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .compare-title {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
  }

  .compare-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Tip card (for /init) */
  .tip-card {
    margin: var(--space-5) 0 var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .tip-title {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .tip-body {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  /* Info card (judgment rule) */
  .info-card {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .info-title {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .info-body {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 500;
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* Code block */
  .code-block {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-text);
    overflow-x: auto;
    white-space: pre;
  }

  .code-block code {
    font-family: inherit;
    background: none;
    padding: 0;
    color: inherit;
  }

  .code-block--command {
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Scenario cards (good vs bad) */
  .scenario-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
  }

  .scenario-card {
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }

  .scenario-tag {
    display: inline-block;
    align-self: flex-start;
    padding: var(--space-1) var(--space-3);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .scenario-tag--good {
    background-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: #fff;
  }

  .scenario-tag--skip {
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .scenario-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-1);
  }

  .scenario-list li {
    padding-left: var(--space-4);
    position: relative;
  }

  .scenario-list li::before {
    content: '·';
    position: absolute;
    left: var(--space-2);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .scenario-note {
    margin: 0;
    padding-top: var(--space-3);
    border-top: 1px dashed var(--color-border);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* Path card */
  .path-card {
    margin: var(--space-5) 0 var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
  }

  .path-label {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .path-body {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .path-body:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .path-code {
    margin: var(--space-2) 0 var(--space-3);
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .path-code code {
    background: none;
    padding: 0;
    color: inherit;
  }

  /* Split grid (CLAUDE.md vs auto memory examples) */
  .split-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin: var(--space-5) 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .split-card {
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    transition: all var(--transition);
  }

  .split-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .split-card--soft {
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
  }

  .split-head {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-3);
    border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--color-border);
  }

  .split-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-2);
  }

  .split-list li {
    padding-left: var(--space-4);
    position: relative;
  }

  .split-list li::before {
    content: '›';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* Warning card */
  .warning-card {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-left: 4px solid #d97706;
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
  }

  .warning-title {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #b45309;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .warning-body {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* Command cards (/compact, /clear, /context) */
  .cmd-list {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
  }

  .cmd-card {
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    transition: all var(--transition);
  }

  .cmd-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    transform: translateX(2px);
  }

  .cmd-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-3);
    border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--color-border);
  }

  .cmd-num {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 2rem;
    height: 2rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: #fff;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .cmd-title {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-1);
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
  }

  .cmd-alias {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .cmd-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .cmd-example {
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .cmd-example-label {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .cmd-example code {
    display: block;
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
